---
import BaseLayout from '@/layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Breadcrumbs from '@/components/Breadcrumbs.astro';
import AffiliateDisclosure from '@/components/AffiliateDisclosure.astro';
import VsComparison from '@/components/VsComparison.astro';
import FAQ from '@/components/FAQ.astro';
import { getProductBySlug } from '@/lib/products';
import { articleSchema, faqSchema, breadcrumbSchema, jsonLdGraph } from '@/lib/seo';

const a = await getProductBySlug('learn-to-solder-jitterbug-kit');
const b = await getProductBySlug('mioyoow-line-following-robot-soldering-kit');
if (!a || !b) throw new Error('Comparison products not found');

const crumbs = [
  { name: 'Home', url: '/' },
  { name: 'Jitterbug vs Robot Car Kit', url: '/jitterbug-vs-robot-car-kit' },
];

const faqs = [
  {
    question: 'Jitterbug or robot car kit — which is better for kids?',
    answer:
      'It depends on the child\'s age and soldering experience. The Jitterbug has only a handful of large, forgiving joints and is finishable in one sitting, making it the better choice for a first-ever solder, especially for younger children. The line-following robot car has more components and teaches sensors and motor control, so it suits an older child or one who has already soldered something before.',
  },
  {
    question: 'What age is appropriate for a kids soldering kit?',
    answer:
      'With direct adult supervision of the hot iron, the Jitterbug works for children as young as about 8, since the build is short and the joints are large. The line-following robot car, with its higher component count and finer work, is better suited to ages 10 and up, or a younger child working alongside an adult. Always supervise any child using a soldering iron.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Do either of these kits include a soldering iron?',
    answer:
      'No — like almost every soldering kit, both include the board, components and (for the Jitterbug) a battery, but you supply your own temperature-controlled iron and solder. See our best soldering irons roundup and pick a station for stable, safe heat around kids.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Which kit holds a kid\'s attention longer after it is built?',
    answer:
      'The robot car tends to win here — a line-following robot invites repeated play as kids test it on different drawn paths, while the Jitterbug\'s appeal (skittering across a table) is real but simpler and fades faster. For a child who wants to keep playing with the result, the robot car is the stronger pick; for the quickest confidence-building first solder, the Jitterbug wins.',
  },
];

const jsonLd = jsonLdGraph(
  articleSchema({
    title: 'Jitterbug vs Robot Car Kit: Best First Soldering Kit for Kids',
    description:
      'Jitterbug vs line-following robot car kit compared — which soldering kit is the better first project for kids, by age, joint count and lasting play value.',
    url: '/jitterbug-vs-robot-car-kit',
    datePublished: '2026-07-01',
    dateModified: '2026-07-01',
  }),
  breadcrumbSchema(crumbs),
  faqSchema(faqs),
);
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Jitterbug vs Robot Car Kit: Best Kids Soldering Kit"
  description="Jitterbug vs line-following robot car kit compared — which is the better first soldering kit for kids? Joint count, age fit and lasting play value, with a clear pick."
  type="article"
  jsonLd={jsonLd}
  publishedTime="2026-07-01"
  modifiedTime="2026-07-01"
>
  <div class="container-px py-8 lg:py-12">
    <Breadcrumbs items={crumbs} />
    <header class="mx-auto mt-6 max-w-3xl">
      <h1 class="text-4xl font-extrabold leading-tight tracking-tight text-ink-900 sm:text-5xl">
        Jitterbug vs Robot Car Kit
      </h1>
      <p class="mt-5 text-lg leading-relaxed text-ink-600">
        Two of the best-loved first soldering kits for kids, and two very different builds. The
        <strong>{a.title}</strong> is over in a handful of joints; the <strong>{b.title}</strong>
        is a bigger project that teaches sensors and motors. Here is how to pick the right one
        for the child (and the afternoon) you have in mind.
      </p>
    </header>

    <div class="mx-auto mt-8 max-w-3xl"><AffiliateDisclosure /></div>

    <div class="mt-12">
      <VsComparison a={a} b={b} />
    </div>

    <section class="prose prose-lg mx-auto mt-16 max-w-3xl">
      <h2>A quick win vs a bigger build</h2>
      <p>
        The <strong>{a.title}</strong> is built for speed and confidence. A handful of large,
        forgiving through-hole joints, a battery, and it skitters across the table — the classic
        workshop staple that has introduced thousands of kids to soldering in a single sitting.
        There is very little to go wrong, which makes it the safer bet for a nervous first-timer
        or a younger child.
      </p>
      <p>
        The <strong>{b.title}</strong> asks for more patience and more joints, but pays it back
        with a robot that actually senses and follows a line you draw yourself. It teaches real
        concepts — sensors, motor control — alongside the soldering, and the open-ended play
        (draw a new track, watch it follow) gives it more lasting appeal than a kit that is
        "done" the moment it is built.
      </p>

      <h2>Choose the {a.title} if…</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>This is the child's very first time holding a soldering iron.</li>
        <li>You want a project finishable in a single sitting.</li>
        <li>The child is younger or you want the simplest possible build.</li>
        <li>You are running a classroom or workshop with limited time.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Choose the {b.title} if…</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>The child has soldered something before, or is 10 and up.</li>
        <li>You want the build to teach sensors and motor control, not just joints.</li>
        <li>Lasting play value after the build matters as much as the build itself.</li>
        <li>You have a bit more time for a longer, more involved project.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Our verdict</h2>
      <p>
        For a genuine first solder, start with the <a href={`/reviews/${a.slug}`}>Jitterbug</a> —
        it is nearly impossible to fail, and that early win matters more than anything else. Once
        a child has one successful build behind them, the
        <a href={`/reviews/${b.slug}`}>line-following robot car</a> is the natural next step up,
        with a result they will keep coming back to. Either way, supervise the iron closely and
        pair the kit with a stable, temperature-controlled station from our
        <a href="/best-soldering-irons">soldering irons roundup</a>. For more gift ideas, see our
        <a href="/best-soldering-kits-for-kids">best soldering kits for kids</a> roundup.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="mt-16"><FAQ faqs={faqs} /></section>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
